 Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Harding","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Harding</i> (Old English <i>Hearding</i>, literally ‘the hard one’ a derivative of Old English <i>heard</i> ‘hard, harsh, strong, firm, brave’). The surname was first taken to Ireland in the 15th century, and more families of the name settled there 200 years later in Tipperary and surrounding counties.","North German and Dutch: patronymic from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic compound personal names beginning with <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’, or a habitational name from a farm named Harding, of the same etymology.","History: Warren Gamaliel Harding (1865–1923), the 29th president of the US, was born on a farm in OH, of English and Scottish stock on his father's side. Early American bearers of this very common name include Joseph Harding who died at Plymouth in 1633. His great-great grandson Seth was a naval officer during the American Revolution."],"variants":[{"name":"Hardin","meanings":["English: variant of   Harding  .","Altered form of French   Hardouin  .","French: from a pet form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names composed of the element <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. This surname is rare in France."]},{"name":"Arduino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Francisco, Jose, Luis, Marina, Alberto, Alfonso, Alturo, Angel, Arturo, Azucena, Basilio, Carlos.  Italian Antonio, Gabino.","Italian and Hispanic: from the personal name <i>Arduino</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, akin to   Harding   2."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph de Harding was born in 1245, in Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord William De Berkeley, was 19 and his mother, Maud de Berkeley, was 16. He married Mary Deprez before 1265, in Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1286, in his hometown, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1245–1286":"1245–1286","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1265–1294":"1265–1294","1226–1272":"1226–1272","1229–Female":"1229–Surnud","8 January 1272":"8. jaanuar 1272","1226":"1226","1245":"1245","Abt 1265":"umbes 1265","1244":"1244","before 1265":"enne 1265","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1272":"1272","1294":"1294","1250":"1250","1229":"1229","Arden Manor and Longcroft Hall, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Cambridge, Stroud, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berkeley, Stroud District, Gloucestershire, England":"Berkeley, Gloucestershire, England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"